nder assignment rules, definiteness marking, and possessive constructions from a synchronic, diachronic, and typological perspective. The languages surveyed include Austronesian languages, Basque, English, German, Hebrew, and Romance languages. The volume contributes to a better understanding not only of the contrasts between proper names and common nouns, but also of formal contrasts between different proper name classes such as personal names, place names, and others.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aEigennamen. 4aMorphologie. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMorphosyntax, Language Typology, Proper Names, Common Nouns.1 aCaro Reina, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaro Reina, Javier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aD’hulst, Yves, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandschuh, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmbrecht, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmbrecht, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJeffay, Elisheva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevkovych, Nataliya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeisenburg, Trudel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNübling, Damaris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReina, Javier Caro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalaberri, Iker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStolz, Thomas, eco